Text: It was a hard fought match by both sides, but the home team Japan takes it 3-1 (21-25, 25-18, 25-22, 25-20). The Czech side will have an opportunity for payback tomorrow, as the two squads face each other again on Sunday in Okayama.

The Czech side responds with an ace from Adam Bartos and a Filip Habr block on Ishikawa, closing the gap to 23-19.

Japan takes a time-out to regroup, and Ishikawa comes back to give his side the edge, a final spike taking the fourth set 25-20, and the match 3-1.

Japan is scrambling on defence to keep the Czech side from fighting back, and so far it's working. Adam Bartos is visibly frustrated, not able to find the attack out wide. In contrast, Shimizu and Suzuki are landing their attacks just fine, and Shimizu contributing an ace to force a Czech time-out. Japan looks to be in control, 22-15 here in the fourth set.
Japan's Yuki Ishikawa is really firing up the hometown crowd today. Another spike from him helps his team jump ahead 16-13 at the second TTO.

Yuki Ishikawa, who has led Japan in scoring with 14 points so far, shows he can do it on defence too. His incredible dig leads to another Japan point as the Czech Republic's Adam Bartos fires a shot long.
Led by Suzuki, Japan continues to block well. His stuff helps Japan edge ahead 9-8, setting up a Kuriyama spike, and another trademark fist pump after the score!
Japan's Shimizu puts away a blistering spike after a hard fought rally by both sides. Japan trails the Czech's by one, 6-5, in the fourth set.

David Konecny attempts another attack on Japan's set point, but this time he's not as lucky, as the ref informs him that a close ball has missed the mark. Japan takes the set 25-22, and goes up two sets to one.

The crowd is sensing a hometown victory as we head into the fourth set! Let's see if it happens.
David Konecny is doing his best to keep the Czech side close, with a spike to draw within two points (23-11), and then a wonderful tip -- showing some finesse -- to make it 23-22.
Japan's Yoshifumi Suzuki frustrates the Czech Republic's Kamil Baranek once again, blocking him for a score to go ahead 21-18. That's his fourth block!

Japan's blockers are really giving Kamil Baranek trouble out wide, with Suzuki and Ishikawa putting consecutive stuffs on him for scores. They jump ahead 15-11 to the delight of the hometown crowd! For Suzuki, it's his third block of the match, a great defensive effort!
Japan's Yuki Ishikawa has been attacking well so far, leading his side with nine points. It's 8-7 Japan at the first TTO.
The Czech side edges ahead early in the third, but Japan is responding tenaciously, Yoshifumi Suzuki firing an ace to draw even at 5-5.

Yoshifumi Suzuki was attacking well for Japan with five of his seven points so far coming in this second set. The Czech side did not help their cause late, with a couple of errant attacks allowing the home side to take the set 25-18 when David Konecny drove a spike long. Lets see if the visitors can be more composed as we head into the third set!
With Japan ahead 19-13, the Czech side opts for Adam Bartos, giving Kamil Baranek a breather. Baranek has led his team with six points so far.

Coach Nambu's confidence in Masashi Kuriyama continues to pay off coming out of the timeout, as the team is coming together well defensively in the face of the attacking Czechs. Kuriyama buried a spike after a wonderful rally to go up 9-5, with a splendid fist pump celebration to fire up the crowd!
Japan's coach Nambu has gone back to Masashi Kuriyama, who is responding well from the service line. Japan is up 7-4 early in the second set, prompting a Czech time-out.

Despite a near net serve from Adam Bartos, the Czech side managed to capitalize on set point, with the captain Ales Holubec sending a spike home to take the first set 25-21. Things have been going the visitors way thus far!

Japan's Masashi Kuriyama was struggling to find an attacking rhythm late in the set, and coach Nambu would try another direction, subbing in Hiroaki Asano at 22-18. But Asano fared no better, missing the mark on a spike to give the Czech side set point 24-21.

Japan's coach Nambu noted yesterday that his team needed to be careful not to make mistakes. With a few service errors already, his team is not living up to that goal. Nevertheless, they remain just two points behind at 18-16.

Both teams are swinging hard to try to get an edge. The visiting Czech team retains an edge, with David Konecny and Jakub Vesely helping Baranek on the attack. For Japan, Shimizu and Ishikawa have countered well to keep the home side close. It's 16-13 at the second TTO.
Kamil Baranek is really hurting Japan with hard-hitting spikes from out wide. Another just found the mark to put the Czech Republic up 9-5.
The visiting Czech Republic are out to an early 4-0 lead on Japan, on an ace by Filip Habr.
Local mascots in Okayama are getting the crowd energised as match time approaches!
It's a beautiful day in Okayama, Japan, as folks are already filing into Momotaro Arena, hoping the home side can pick up a win against the visiting Czech Republic!
